@misha1109 Will `APP_INITIALIZER` work?

Example:
```ts
export default {
  title: 'core/pricing',
  component: PricingComponent,
  decorators: [
    moduleMetadata({
      imports: [PipesModule, DirectivesModule, BodyModule],
      declarations: [AppComponent]
    })
  ]
} as Meta;

function initPricingFactory(pricingService: PricingService) {
  return () => pricingService.initPricing(mockPricing, mockCurrency)
}

const Template: Story<PricingComponent> = (args: PricingComponent) => ({
  moduleMetadata: {
    providers: [
      {
        provide: APP_INITIALIZER,
        useFactory: initPricingFactory,
        multi: true,
        deps: [PricingService]
      }
    ]
  },
  component: PricingComponent,
  props: args,
});

export const Primary = Template.bind({});
Primary.args = {
};
```

Without knowing more about your data and service, I don't know if the following would work, but could you just inject an alternate class for PricingService? That way you could just avoid the calculations also, since the data is just mocked anyway.

Example:
```ts
export default {
  title: 'core/pricing',
  component: PricingComponent,
  decorators: [
    moduleMetadata({
      imports: [PipesModule, DirectivesModule, BodyModule],
      declarations: [AppComponent]
    })
  ]
} as Meta;

class MockPricingService implements Partial<PricingService> {
  getPricing = () => mockPricingData
}

const Template: Story<PricingComponent> = (args: PricingComponent) => ({
  moduleMetadata: {
    providers: [
      { provide: PricingService, useClass: MockPricingService }
    ]
  },
  component: PricingComponent,
  props: args,
});

export const Primary = Template.bind({});
Primary.args = {
};
```

@silvicardo thank for bringing this to our attention and sorry for the delay in updating the documentation.

I've created a pull request addressing the issue and will soon be merged.

Stay safe

